First note that for each prime p∈{7,11,13} the quadratic‐residues in {0,1,…,6} are

 p=7: {0,1,2,4}  
 p=11:{0,1,3,4,5}  
 p=13:{0,1,3,4}

Their intersection is {0,1,4}.  Hence if n²≡r mod 7,11,13 with 0≤r≤6 then r∈{0,1,4}.  

– For r=0 there is exactly 1 solution mod 7, 1 mod 11, 1 mod 13 ⇒ 1 solution mod 1001.  
– For r=1 (resp. r=4) each is a nonzero square mod p, so 2 solutions mod 7, 2 mod 11, 2 mod 13 ⇒ 2³=8 solutions mod 1001.  

In all 1+8+8=17 solutions modulo 1001.  Since 2018=2·1001+16, in the range 1≤n<2018 each residue class mod 1001 occurs exactly twice in 1…2002, plus for n=2003…2017 (that is the last 15 values) one more if its representative lies in {1,…,15}.  A quick check shows only n=1,2 among 1…15 work.  Hence the total count is  

2·17 + 2 = 34 + 2 = 36.  

Answer: \boxed{36}.

